                                                                    <h4><em><a href="/">Journal of Management Information Systems</a></em></h4>
                                                                
        
    <div><a href="/issues/114">    Volume 2 Number 4 1986
</a> pp. 85-97</div>
                                
                                    <div class="margin-bottom-5">
        <h3>Systems to Think With: A Response to &quot;A Vision for Decision Support Systems&quot;</h3>
    </div>
    <div class="margin-bottom-10">
            <a href="/contributors/1199">Weber, E Sue</a>    </div>

<p>ABSTRACT: This paper addresses the question of how Decision Support Systems, (DSS) should be designed to stimulate learning and creativity. Research has shown that increasing one's use of learning and problem-solving strategies can significantly improve performance. Based on this perspective, the DSS designer's responsibility becomes one of providing strategies that facilitate learning and creative thinking.</p>

    <strong>Key words and phrases: </strong>
        <a href="/keywords/148">problem-solving strategies</a>,    <a href="/keywords/149">creativity in decision making</a>,    <a href="/keywords/39">decision support systems</a>
                                
                        
